[src:yup-validation/api-formdata] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:yup-validation/api-formdata] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:yup-validation/api-formdata] The **`FormData`** interface provides a way to construct a set of key/value pairs representing form fields and their values, which can be sent using the `fetch()`, `XMLHttpRequest.send()` or `navigator.sendBeacon()` methods.
[src:yup-validation/api-formdata] It uses the same format a form would use if the encoding type were set to `"multipart/form-data"`.
[src:yup-validation/api-formdata] You can also pass it directly to the `URLSearchParams` constructor if you want to generate query parameters in the way a `<form>` would do if it were using simple `GET` submission.
[src:yup-validation/api-formdata] An object implementing `FormData` can directly be used in a `for...of` structure, instead of `entries()`: `for (const p of myFormData)` is equivalent to `for (const p of myFormData.entries())`.
[src:yup-validation/api-formdata] Appends a new value onto an existing key inside a `FormData` object, or adds the key if it does not already exist.
[src:yup-validation/api-formdata] Deletes a key/value pair from a `FormData` object.
[src:yup-validation/api-formdata] Returns an iterator that iterates through all key/value pairs contained in the `FormData`.
[src:yup-validation/api-formdata] Returns the first value associated with a given key from within a `FormData` object.
[src:yup-validation/api-formdata] Returns an array of all the values associated with a given key from within a `FormData`.
[src:yup-validation/api-formdata] Returns whether a `FormData` object contains a certain key.
[src:yup-validation/api-formdata] Returns an iterator iterates through all keys of the key/value pairs contained in the `FormData`.
[src:yup-validation/api-formdata] Sets a new value for an existing key inside a `FormData` object, or adds the key/value if it does not already exist.
[src:yup-validation/api-formdata] Returns an iterator that iterates through all values contained in the `FormData`.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] In computing, **data validation** or **input validation** is the process of ensuring data has undergone data cleansing to confirm it has data quality, that is, that it is both correct and useful.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] It uses routines, often called "validation rules", "validation constraints", or "check routines", that check for correctness, meaningfulness, and security of data that are input to the system.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] The rules may be implemented through the automated facilities of a data dictionary, or by the inclusion of explicit application program validation logic of the computer and its application.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] This is distinct from formal verification, which attempts to prove or disprove the correctness of algorithms for implementing a specification or property.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Data validation is intended to provide certain well-defined guarantees for fitness and consistency of data in an application or automated system.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Data validation rules can be defined and designed using various methodologies, and be deployed in various contexts.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Their implementation can use declarative data integrity rules, or procedure-based business rules.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] The guarantees of data validation do not necessarily include accuracy, and it is possible for data entry errors such as misspellings to be accepted as valid.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Other clerical and/or computer controls may be applied to reduce inaccuracy within a system.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] In evaluating the basics of data validation, generalizations can be made regarding the different kinds of validation according to their scope, complexity, and purpose.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Data type validation is customarily carried out on one or more simple data fields.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] The simplest kind of data type validation verifies that the individual characters provided through user input are consistent with the expected characters of one or more known primitive data types as defined in a programming language or data storage and retrieval mechanism.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] For example, an integer field may require input to use only characters 0 through 9.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Simple range and constraint validation may examine input for consistency with a minimum/maximum range, or consistency with a test for evaluating a sequence of characters, such as one or more tests against regular expressions.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] For example, a counter value may be required to be a non-negative integer, and a password may be required to meet a minimum length and contain characters from multiple categories.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Code and cross-reference validation includes operations to verify that data is consistent with one or more possibly-external rules, requirements, or collections relevant to a particular organization, context or set of underlying assumptions.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] These additional validity constraints may involve cross-referencing supplied data with a known look-up table or directory information service such as LDAP.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] For example, a user-provided country code might be required to identify a current geopolitical region.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Structured validation allows for the combination of other kinds of validation, along with more complex processing.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Such complex processing may include the testing of conditional constraints for an entire complex data object or set of process operations within a system.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Consistency validation ensures that data is logical.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] For example, the delivery date of an order can be prohibited from preceding its shipment date.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Multiple kinds of data validation are relevant to 10-digit pre-2007 ISBNs (the 2005 edition of ISO 2108 required ISBNs to have 13 digits from 2007 onwards).
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Checks to ascertain that only expected characters are present in a field.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] For example a numeric field may only allow the digits 0–9, the decimal point and perhaps a minus sign or commas.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] An e-mail address might require at least one @ sign and various other structural details.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] can be effective ways to implement such checks.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Numerical fields may be added together for all records in a batch.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] The batch total is entered and the computer checks that the total is correct, e.g., add the 'Total Cost' field of a number of transactions together.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Checks that record has a valid number of related records.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] For example, if a contact record is classified as "customer" then it must have at least one associated order (cardinality > 0).
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] This type of rule can be complicated by additional conditions.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] For example, if a contact record in a payroll database is classified as "former employee" then it must not have any associated salary payments after the separation date (cardinality = 0).
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] To support error detection, an extra digit is added to a number which is calculated from the other digits.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Checks fields to ensure data in these fields correspond, e.g., if expiration date is in the past then status is not "active".
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Compares data in different systems to ensure it is consistent.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Systems may represent the same data differently, in which case comparison requires transformation (e.g., one system may store customer name in a single Name field as 'Doe, John Q', while another uses First_Name 'John' and Last_Name 'Doe' and Middle_Name 'Quality').
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Checks input conformance with typed data.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] For example, an input box accepting numeric data may reject the letter 'O'.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Checks that a file with a specified name exists.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] This check is essential for programs that use file handling.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Checks that the data is in a specified format (template), e.g., dates have to be in the format YYYY-MM-DD.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Regular expressions may be used for this kind of validation.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Checks that data is present, e.g., customers may be required to have an email address.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Checks that the data is within a specified range of values, e.g., a probability must be between 0 and 1.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] tables can be linked through foreign key and primary key.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] If values in the foreign key field are not constrained by internal mechanisms, then they should be validated to ensure that the referencing table always refers to a row in the referenced table.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Looks for spelling and grammatical errors.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] This can be applied to several fields (i.e.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] A table look up check compares data to a collection of allowed values.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Enforcement action typically rejects the data entry request and requires the input actor to make a change that brings the data into compliance.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] This is most suitable for interactive use, where a real person is sitting on the computer and making entry.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] It also works well for batch upload, where a file input may be rejected and a set of messages sent back to the input source for why the data is rejected.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Another form of enforcement action involves automatically changing the data and saving a conformant version instead of the original version.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] This is most suitable for cosmetic change.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] For example, converting an [all-caps] entry to a [Pascal case] entry does not need user input.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] An inappropriate use of automatic enforcement would be in situations where the enforcement leads to loss of business information.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] For example, saving a truncated comment if the length is longer than expected.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] This is not typically a good thing since it may result in loss of significant data.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Advisory actions typically allow data to be entered unchanged but sends a message to the source actor indicating those validation issues that were encountered.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] This is most suitable for non-interactive system, for systems where the change is not business critical, for cleansing steps of existing data and for verification steps of an entry process.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Verification actions are special cases of advisory actions.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] In this case, the source actor is asked to verify that this data is what they would really want to enter, in the light of a suggestion to the contrary.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Here, the check step suggests an alternative (e.g., a check of a mailing address returns a different way of formatting that address or suggests a different address altogether).
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] You would want in this case, to give the user the option of accepting the recommendation or keeping their version.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] This is not a strict validation process, by design and is useful for capturing addresses to a new location or to a location that is not yet supported by the validation databases.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Even in cases where data validation did not find any issues, providing a log of validations that were conducted and their results is important.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Failures or omissions in data validation can lead to data corruption or a security vulnerability.
[src:yup-validation/data-validation] Data validation checks that data are fit for purpose, valid, sensible, reasonable and secure before they are processed.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] The **database schema** is the structure of a database described in a formal language supported typically by a relational database management system (RDBMS).
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] The term "schema" refers to the organization of data as a blueprint of how the database is constructed (divided into database tables in the case of relational databases).
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] The formal definition of a database schema is a set of formulas (sentences) called integrity constraints imposed on a database.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] These integrity constraints ensure compatibility between parts of the schema.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] All constraints are expressible in the same language.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] A database can be considered a structure in realization of the database language.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] The states of a created conceptual schema are transformed into an explicit mapping, the database schema.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] This describes how real-world entities are modeled in the database.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] "A database schema specifies, based on the database administrator's knowledge of possible applications, the facts that can enter the database, or those of interest to the possible end-users." The notion of a database schema plays the same role as the notion of theory in predicate calculus.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] A model of this "theory" closely corresponds to a database, which can be seen at any instant of time as a mathematical object.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] Thus a schema can contain formulas representing integrity constraints specifically for an application and the constraints specifically for a type of database, all expressed in the same database language.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] In a relational database, the schema defines the tables, fields, relationships, views, indexes, packages, procedures, functions, queues, triggers, types, sequences, materialized views, synonyms, database links, directories, XML schemas, and other elements.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] A database generally stores its schema in a data dictionary.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] Although a schema is defined in text database language, the term is often used to refer to a graphical depiction of the database structure.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] In other words, schema is the structure of the database that defines the objects in the database.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] In an Oracle Database system, the term "schema" has a slightly different connotation.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] The requirements listed below influence the detailed structure of schemas that are produced.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] Certain applications will not require that all of these conditions are met, but these four requirements are the most ideal.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] Each of the overlapping elements specified in the input mapping is also in a database schema relation.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] Source-specific elements that are associated with a source’s overlapping elements are passed through to the database schema.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] Independent entities and relationships in the source data should not be grouped together in the same relation in the database schema.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] In particular, source specific schema elements should not be grouped with overlapping schema elements, if the grouping co-locates independent entities or relationships.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] If any elements of the database schema are dropped then the database schema is not ideal.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] Suppose we want a mediated schema to integrate two travel databases, Go-travel and Ok-flight.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] In the context of Oracle Databases, a **schema object** is a logical data storage structure.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] An Oracle database associates a separate schema with each database **user**.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] A schema comprises a collection of schema objects.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] Schema objects do not have a one-to-one correspondence to physical files on disk that store their information.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] However, Oracle databases store schema objects logically within a tablespace of the database.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] The data of each object is physically contained in one or more of the tablespace's datafiles.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] For some objects (such as tables, indexes, and clusters) a database administrator can specify how much disk space the Oracle RDBMS allocates for the object within the tablespace's datafiles.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] There is no necessary relationship between schemas and tablespaces: a tablespace can contain objects from different schemas, and the objects for a single schema can reside in different tablespaces.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] Oracle database specificity does, however, enforce platform recognition of nonhomogenized sequence differentials, which is considered a crucial limiting factor in virtualized applications.
[src:yup-validation/database-schema] In Microsoft SQL Server, the default schema of every database is the dbo schema.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] The **`Object`** type represents one of JavaScript's data types.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] It is used to store various keyed collections and more complex entities.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] Objects can be created using the `Object()` constructor or the object initializer / literal syntax.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] Nearly all objects in JavaScript are instances of `Object`; a typical object inherits properties (including methods) from `Object.prototype`, although these properties may be shadowed (a.k.a. overridden).
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] The only objects that don't inherit from `Object.prototype` are those with `null` prototype, or descended from other `null` prototype objects.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] Changes to the `Object.prototype` object are seen by **all** objects through prototype chaining, unless the properties and methods subject to those changes are overridden further along the prototype chain.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] This provides a very powerful although potentially dangerous mechanism to override or extend object behavior.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] To make it more secure, `Object.prototype` is the only object in the core JavaScript language that has immutable prototype — the prototype of `Object.prototype` is always `null` and not changeable.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] You should avoid calling any of the `Object.prototype` methods directly from the instance, especially those that are not intended to be polymorphic (i.e., only its initial behavior makes sense and no descending object could override it in a meaningful way).
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] All objects descending from `Object.prototype` may define a custom own property that has the same name, but with entirely different semantics from what you expect.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] Furthermore, these properties are not inherited by `null`-prototype objects.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] All modern JavaScript utilities for working with objects are static.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] There isn't any method in an Object itself to delete its own properties (such as `Map.prototype.delete()`).
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] To do so, one must use the `delete` operator.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] Almost all objects in JavaScript ultimately inherit from `Object.prototype` (see inheritance and the prototype chain).
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] However, you may create `null`-prototype objects using `Object.create(null)` or the object initializer syntax with `__proto__: null` (note: the `__proto__` key in object literals is different from the deprecated `Object.prototype.__proto__` property).
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] You can also change the prototype of an existing object to `null` by calling `Object.setPrototypeOf(obj, null)`.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] An object with a `null` prototype can behave in unexpected ways, because it doesn't inherit any object methods from `Object.prototype`.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] This is especially true when debugging, since common object-property converting/detecting utility functions may generate errors, or lose information (especially if using silent error-traps that ignore errors).
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] Unlike normal objects, in which `toString()` is on the object's prototype, the `toString()` method here is an own property of `nullProtoObj`.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] This is because `nullProtoObj` has no (`null`) prototype.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] You can also revert a null-prototype object back to an ordinary object using `Object.setPrototypeOf(nullProtoObj, Object.prototype)`.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] In practice, objects with `null` prototype are usually used as a cheap substitute for maps.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] In such case, the addition of any method should be done cautiously, as they can be confused with the other key-value pairs stored as data.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] Making your object not inherit from `Object.prototype` also prevents prototype pollution attacks.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] If a malicious script adds a property to `Object.prototype`, it will be accessible on every object in your program, except objects that have null prototype.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] JavaScript also has built-in APIs that produce `null`-prototype objects, especially those that use objects as ad hoc key-value collections.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] The term "`null`-prototype object" often also includes any object without `Object.prototype` in its prototype chain.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] Such objects can be created with `extends null` when using classes.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] Many built-in operations that expect objects first coerce their arguments to objects.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] There are two ways to achieve nearly the same effect in JavaScript.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] Unlike conversion to primitives, the object coercion process itself is not observable in any way, since it doesn't invoke custom code like `toString` or `valueOf` methods.
