[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] When altering the behavior of existing `Object.prototype` methods, consider injecting code by wrapping your extension before or after the existing logic.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] For example, this (untested) code will pre-conditionally execute custom logic before the built-in logic or someone else's extension is executed.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] When modifying prototypes with hooks, pass `this` and the arguments (the call state) to the current behavior by calling `apply()` on the function.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] This pattern can be used for any prototype, such as `Node.prototype`, `Function.prototype`, etc.
[src:yup-validation/global-objects-object] You can read more about prototypes in Inheritance and the prototype chain.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Yup is a schema builder for runtime value parsing and validation.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Define a schema, transform a value to match, assert the shape of an existing value, or both.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Yup schema are extremely expressive and allow modeling complex, interdependent validations, or value transformation.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Schema are comprised of parsing actions (transforms) as well as assertions (tests) about the input value.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Validate an input value to parse it and run the configured set of assertions.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Chain together methods to build a schema.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Use a schema to coerce or "cast" an input value into the correct type, and optionally transform that value into more concrete and specific values, without making further assertions.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Know that your input value is already parsed?
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] You can "strictly" validate an input, and avoid the overhead of running parsing logic.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Schema definitions, are comprised of parsing "transforms" which manipulate inputs into the desired shape and type, "tests", which make assertions over parsed data.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Schema also store a bunch of "metadata", details about the schema itself, which can be used to improve error messages, build tools that dynamically consume schema, or serialize schema into another format.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Each built-in type implements basic type parsing, which comes in handy when parsing serialized data, such as JSON.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Additionally types implement type specific transforms that can be enabled.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Transforms form a "pipeline", where the value of a previous transform is piped into the next one.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] When an input value is `undefined` yup will apply the schema default if it's configured.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Yup schema run "tests" over input values.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Tests assert that inputs conform to some criteria.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Tests are distinct from transforms, in that they do not change or alter the input (or its type) and are usually reserved for checks that are hard, if not impossible, to represent in static types.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] In the simplest case a test function returns `true` or `false` depending on the whether the check passed.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] In the case of a failing test, yup will throw a `ValidationError` with your (or the default) message for that test.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] ValidationErrors also contain a bunch of other metadata about the test, including it's name, what arguments (if any) it was called with, and the path to the failing field in the case of a nested validation.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Error messages can also be constructed on the fly to customize how the schema fails.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Schema are immutable, each method call returns a new schema object.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Reuse and pass them around without fear of mutating another instance.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Yup schema produce static TypeScript interfaces.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] A schema's default is used when casting produces an `undefined` output value.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Because of this, setting a default affects the output type of the schema, essentially marking it as "defined()".
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] You can use TypeScript's interface merging behavior to extend the schema types if needed.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Type extensions should go in an "ambient" type definition file such as your `globals.d.ts`.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Remember to actually extend the yup type in your application code!
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] You **must** have the `strictNullChecks` compiler option enabled for type inference to work.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] We also recommend settings `strictFunctionTypes` to `false`, for functionally better types.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Your mileage will vary, but we've found that this check doesn't prevent many of real bugs, while increasing the amount of onerous explicit type casting in apps.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] Default error messages can be customized for when no message is provided with a validation test.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] If any message is missing in the custom dictionary the error message will default to Yup's one.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] If you need multi-language support, yup has got you covered.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] The function `setLocale` accepts functions that can be used to generate error objects with translation keys and values.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p01] These can be fed it into your favorite i18n library.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] For nested schemas, `reach` will retrieve an inner schema based on the provided path.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] For nested schemas that need to resolve dynamically, you can provide a `value` and optionally a `context` object.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Adds a new method to the core schema types.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] A friendlier convenience method for `schemaType.prototype[name] = method`.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Creates a reference to another sibling or sibling descendant field.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Refs are resolved at *validation/cast time* and supported where specified.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Refs are evaluated in the proper order so that the ref value is resolved before the field using the ref (be careful of circular dependencies!).
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Creates a schema that is evaluated at validation/cast time.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Useful for creating recursive schema like Trees, for polymorphic fields and arrays.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] `Schema` is the abstract base class that all schema type inherit from.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] It provides a number of base methods and properties to all other schema types.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Clone is used internally to return a new schema with every schema state change.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Overrides the key name which is used in error messages.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Adds to a metadata object, useful for storing data with a schema, that doesn't belong to the cast object itself.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] A custom `SchemaMetadata` interface can be defined through merging with the `CustomSchemaMetadata` interface.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Collects schema details (like meta, labels, and active tests) into a serializable description object.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] For schema with dynamic components (references, lazy, or conditions), describe requires more context to accurately return the schema description.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] And below are the description types, which differ a bit depending on the schema type.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Creates a new instance of the schema by combining two schemas.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Only schemas of the same type can be concatenated.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] `concat` is not a "merge" function in the sense that all settings from the provided schema, override ones in the base, including type, presence and nullability.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Returns the parses and validates an input value, returning the parsed value or throwing an error.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] This method is **asynchronous** and returns a Promise object, that is fulfilled with the value, or rejected with a `ValidationError`.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Provide `options` to more specifically control the behavior of `validate`.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Runs validatations synchronously *if possible* and returns the resulting value, or throws a ValidationError.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Accepts all the same options as `validate`.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Synchronous validation only works if there are no configured async tests, e.g tests that return a Promise.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Validate a deeply nested path within the schema.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Similar to how `reach` works, but uses the resulting schema as the subject for validation.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Returns `true` when the passed in value matches the schema.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] `isValid` is **asynchronous** and returns a Promise object.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Synchronously returns `true` when the passed in value matches the schema.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Takes the same options as `validateSync()` and has the same caveats around async tests.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Attempts to coerce the passed in value to a value that matches the schema.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] For example: `'5'` will cast to `5` when using the `number()` type.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Failed casts generally return `null`, but may also return results like `NaN` and unexpected strings.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Runs a type check against the passed in `value`.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] It returns true if it matches, it does not cast the value.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] When `nullable()` is set `null` is considered a valid value of the type.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] You should use `isType` for all Schema type checks.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Strict schemas skip coercion and transformation attempts, validating the value "as is".
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Marks a schema to be removed from an output object.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] `withMutation` allows you to mutate the schema in place, instead of the default behavior which clones before each change.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Generally this isn't necessary since the vast majority of schema changes happen during the initial declaration, and only happen once over the lifetime of the schema, so performance isn't an issue.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] However certain mutations *do* occur at cast/validation time, (such as conditional schema using `when()`), or when instantiating a schema object.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Sets a default value to use when the value is `undefined`.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Defaults are created after transformations are executed, but before validations, to help ensure that safe defaults are specified.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] The default value will be cloned on each use, which can incur performance penalty for objects and arrays.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] To avoid this overhead you can also pass a function that returns a new default.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Note that `null` is considered a separate non-empty value.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Retrieve a previously set default value.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] `getDefault` will resolve any conditions that may alter the default.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Optionally pass `options` with `context` (for more info on `context` see `Schema.validate`).
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Indicates that `null` is a valid value for the schema.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Without `nullable()` `null` is treated as a different type and will fail `Schema.isType()` checks.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] The opposite of `nullable`, removes `null` from valid type values for the schema.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] All field values apart from `undefined` meet this requirement.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] The opposite of `defined()` allows `undefined` values for the given type.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Mark the schema as required, which will not allow `undefined` or `null` as a value.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Define an error message for failed type checks.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] The `${value}` and `${type}` interpolation can be used in the `message` argument.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Values added are removed from any `notOneOf` values if present.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] The `${values}` interpolation can be used in the `message` argument.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] If a ref or refs are provided, the `${resolved}` interpolation can be used in the message argument to get the resolved values that were checked at validation time.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Note that `undefined` does not fail this validator, even when `undefined` is not included in `arrayOfValues`.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] If you don't want `undefined` to be a valid value, you can use `Schema.required`.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Values added are removed from `oneOf` values if present.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Adjust the schema based on a sibling or sibling children fields.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] You can provide an object literal where the key `is` is value or a matcher function, `then` provides the true schema and/or `otherwise` for the failure condition.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] `is` conditions are strictly compared (`===`) if you want to use a different form of equality you can provide a function like: `is: (value) => value == true`.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] You can also prefix properties with `$` to specify a property that is dependent on `context` passed in by `validate()` or `cast` instead of the input value.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] `then` and `otherwise` are specified functions `(schema: Schema) => Schema`.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] You can also specify more than one dependent key, in which case each value will be spread as an argument.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Alternatively you can provide a function that returns a schema, called with an array of values for each provided key the current schema.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Adds a test function to the validation chain.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Many types have some tests built in, but you can create custom ones easily.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] In order to allow asynchronous custom validations *all* (or no) tests are run asynchronously.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] A consequence of this is that test execution order cannot be guaranteed.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] All tests must provide a `name`, an error `message` and a validation function that must return `true` when the current `value` is valid and `false` or a `ValidationError` otherwise.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] To make a test async return a promise that resolves `true` or `false` or a `ValidationError`.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] For the `message` argument you can provide a string which will interpolate certain values if specified using the `${param}` syntax.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] By default all test messages are passed a `path` value which is valuable in nested schemas.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] The `test` function is called with the current `value`.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Test functions are called with a special context value, as the second argument, that exposes some useful metadata and functions.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] For non arrow functions, the test context is also set as the function `this`.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Watch out, if you access it via `this` it won't work in an arrow function.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] In the case of mixing exclusive and non-exclusive tests the following logic is used.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] If a non-exclusive test is added to a schema with an exclusive test of the same name the exclusive test is removed and further tests of the same name will be stacked.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] If an exclusive test is added to a schema with non-exclusive tests of the same name the previous tests are removed and further tests of the same name will replace each other.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Adds a transformation to the transform chain.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Transformations are central to the casting process, default transforms for each type coerce values to the specific type (as verified by `isType()`). transforms are run before validations and only applied when the schema is not marked as `strict` (the default).
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Some types have built in transformations.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Each types will handle basic coercion of values to the proper type for you, but occasionally you may want to adjust or refine the default behavior.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] For example, if you wanted to use a different date parsing strategy than the default one you could do that with a transform.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Creates a schema that matches all types, or just the ones you configure.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Mixed types extends `{}` by default instead of `any` or `unknown`.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] This is because in TypeScript `{}` means anything that isn't `null` or `undefined` which yup treats distinctly.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Custom types can be implemented by passing a type `check` function.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] This will also narrow the TypeScript type for the schema.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] By default, the `cast` logic of `string` is to call `toString` on the value if it exists.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] empty values are not coerced (use `ensure()` to coerce empty values to empty strings).
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] The same as the `mixed()` schema required, **except** that empty strings are also considered 'missing' values.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Set a required length for the string value.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Set a minimum length limit for the string value.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Set a maximum length limit for the string value.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Provide an arbitrary `regex` to match the value against.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] An alternate signature for `string.matches` with an options object.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] `excludeEmptyString`, when true, short circuits the regex test when the value is an empty string, making it a easier to avoid matching nothing without complicating the regex.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Validates the value as an email address using the same regex as defined by the HTML spec.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] WATCH OUT: Validating email addresses is nearly impossible with just code.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Different clients and servers accept different things and many diverge from the various specs defining "valid" emails.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] The ONLY real way to validate an email address is to send a verification email to it and check that the user got it.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] With that in mind, yup picks a relatively simple regex that does not cover all cases, but aligns with browser input validation behavior since HTML forms are a common use case for yup.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Validates the value as a valid URL via a regex.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Validates the value as a valid UUID via a regex.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Validates the value as an ISO datetime via a regex.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Defaults to UTC validation; timezone offsets are not permitted (see `options.allowOffset`).
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Unlike `.date()`, `datetime` will not convert the string to a `Date` object.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] `datetime` also provides greater customization over the required format of the datetime string than `date` does.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] `options.allowOffset`: Allow a time zone offset.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] *(default: false)* `options.precision`: Require a certain sub-second precision on the date.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] An alternate signature for `string.datetime` that can be used when you don't need to pass options other than `message`.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Transforms `undefined` and `null` values to an empty string along with setting the `default` to an empty string.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Transforms string values by removing leading and trailing whitespace.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] If `strict()` is set it will only validate that the value is trimmed.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Transforms the string value to lowercase.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] If `strict()` is set it will only validate that the value is lowercase.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Transforms the string value to uppercase.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] If `strict()` is set it will only validate that the value is uppercase.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] The default `cast` logic of `number` is: `parseFloat`.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] The `${min}` interpolation can be used in the `message` argument.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] The `${max}` interpolation can be used in the `message` argument.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] The `${less}` interpolation can be used in the `message` argument.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Value must be strictly greater than `min`.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] The `${more}` interpolation can be used in the `message` argument.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Transformation that coerces the value to an integer by stripping off the digits to the right of the decimal point.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Adjusts the value via the specified method of `Math` (defaults to 'round').
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] By default ISO date strings will parse correctly, for more robust parsing options see the extending schema types at the end of the readme.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] The default `cast` logic of `date` is pass the value to the `Date` constructor, failing that, it will attempt to parse the date as an ISO date string.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] When a string is provided it will attempt to cast to a date first and use the result as the limit.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Set the maximum date allowed, When a string is provided it will attempt to cast to a date first and use the result as the limit.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Arrays can be typed or not, When specifying the element type, `cast` and `isValid` will apply to the elements as well.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Options passed into `isValid` are also passed to child schemas.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] You can also pass a subtype schema to the array constructor as a convenience.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Arrays have no default casting behavior.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] `of()` is optional and when omitted the array schema will not validate its contents.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Attempt to parse input string values as JSON using `JSON.parse`.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Set a specific length requirement for the array.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] The `${length}` interpolation can be used in the `message` argument.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Set a minimum length limit for the array.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Set a maximum length limit for the array.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Ensures that the value is an array, by setting the default to `[]` and transforming `null` and `undefined` values to an empty array as well.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Any non-empty, non-array value will be wrapped in an array.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Providing a rejecter function lets you specify the rejection criteria yourself.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Tuples, are fixed length arrays where each item has a distinct type.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] tuples have no default casting behavior.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] object schema do not have any default transforms applied.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] This may be a bit surprising, but is usually helpful since it allows large, nested schema to create default values that fill out the whole shape and not just the root object.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] During the validation phase `names` exists, and is validated, finding `names.first` missing.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Define the keys of the object and the schemas for said keys.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Note that you can chain `shape` method, which acts like `Object.assign`.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Creates a object schema, by applying all settings and fields from `schemaB` to the base, producing a new schema.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] The object shape is shallowly merged with common fields from `schemaB` taking precedence over the base fields.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Create a new schema from a subset of the original's fields.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Create a new schema with fields omitted.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Transforms the specified key to a new key.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] If `alias` is `true` then the old key will be left.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] The same as `object().validate(value, { stripUnknown: true})`, but as a transform method.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] When set any unknown properties will be removed.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Validate that the object value only contains keys specified in `shape`, pass `false` as the first argument to disable the check.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Restricting keys to known, also enables `stripUnknown` option, when not in strict mode.
[src:yup-validation/jquense-yup-p02] Transforms all object keys to CONSTANT_CASE.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] A programming language consists of a system of allowed sequences of symbols (constructs) together with rules that define how each construct is interpreted.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] For example, a language might allow expressions representing various types of data, expressions that provide structuring rules for data, expressions representing various operations on data, and constructs that provide sequencing rules for the order in which to perform operations.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] A simple type system for a programming language is a set of rules that associates a *data type* (for example, integer, floating point, string) with each *term* (data-valued expression) in a computer program.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] In more ambitious type systems, a variety of constructs, such as variables, expressions, functions, and modules, may be assigned types.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Type systems formalize and enforce the otherwise implicit categories the programmer uses for algebraic data types, data structures, or other data types, such as "string", "array of float", "function returning boolean".
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The main purpose of a type system in a programming language is to reduce possibilities for bugs in computer programs due to mismatches in how values are interpreted in different parts of a program.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The aim is to prevent operations expecting a certain kind of value from being applied to values for which that operation does not make sense (validity errors).
[src:yup-validation/type-system] A type system can detect and prevent some of these mismatches.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] When a type mismatch is detected, it is called a type error.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The type of a term constrains the contexts in which it may be used.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] For a variable, the type system determines the allowed values of that variable.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] For that variable to be presented as a parameter to an operation, the operation must be able to accept in that parameter any value that the type of the variable allows.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Type systems are typically specified as part of programming language design.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] They are built into interpreters and compilers for the language.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] In some languages, the type system can be extended by optional tools that perform added checks using the language's original type syntax and grammar.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Type systems allow defining interfaces between different parts of a computer program, and then checking that the parts have been connected in a consistent way.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] This checking can happen statically (at compile time), dynamically (at runtime), or as a combination of both.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Type systems have other purposes as well, such as expressing business rules, enabling certain compiler optimizations, allowing for multiple dispatch, and providing a form of documentation.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] An example of a simple type system is that of the C language.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The portions of a C program are the function definitions.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] One function is invoked by another function.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The interface of a function states the name of the function and a list of parameters that are passed to the function's code.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The code of an invoking function states the name of the invoked, along with the names of variables that hold values to pass to it.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] During a computer program's execution, the values are placed into temporary storage, then execution jumps to the code of the invoked function.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The invoked function's code accesses the values and makes use of them.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] If the instructions inside the function are written with the assumption of receiving an integer value, but the calling code passed a floating-point value, then the wrong result will be computed by the invoked function.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The C compiler checks the types of the arguments passed to a function when it is called against the types of the parameters declared in the function's definition.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] If the types do not match, the compiler throws a compile-time error or warning.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] A compiler may also use the static type of a value to optimize the storage it needs and the choice of algorithms for operations on the value.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] In many C compilers the *float* data type, for example, is represented in 32 bits, in accord with the IEEE specification for single-precision floating point numbers.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] They will thus use floating-point-specific microprocessor operations on those values (floating-point addition, multiplication, etc.).
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The depth of type constraints and the manner of their evaluation affect the *typing* of the language.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] A programming language may further associate an operation with various resolutions for each type, in the case of type polymorphism.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Type theory is the study of type systems.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The concrete types of some programming languages, such as integers and strings, depend on practical issues of computer architecture, compiler implementation, and language design.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Formally, type theory studies type systems.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] A programming language must have the opportunity to type check using the *type system* whether at compile time or runtime, manually annotated or automatically inferred.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Assigning a data type, termed *typing*, gives meaning to a sequence of bits such as a value in memory or some object such as a variable.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Associating a sequence of bits with a type conveys that meaning to the programmable hardware to form a *symbolic system* composed of that hardware and some program.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] A program associates each value with at least one specific type, but it also can occur that one value is associated with many subtypes.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Other entities, such as objects, modules, communication channels, and dependencies can become associated with a type.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Even a type can become associated with a type.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] An implementation of a *type system* could in theory associate identifications called *data type* (a type of a value), *class* (a type of an object), and *kind* (a *type of a type*, or metatype).
[src:yup-validation/type-system] These are the abstractions that typing can go through, on a hierarchy of levels contained in a system.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] It is challenging to find a sufficiently expressive type system that satisfies all programming practices in a type safe manner.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] A programming language compiler can also implement a *dependent type* or an *effect system*, which enables even more program specifications to be verified by a type checker.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Beyond simple value-type pairs, a virtual "region" of code is associated with an "effect" component describing *what* is being done *with what*, and enabling for example to "throw" an error report.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Thus the symbolic system may be a *type and effect system*, which endows it with more safety checking than type checking alone.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Whether automated by the compiler or specified by a programmer, a type system renders program behavior illegal if it falls outside the type-system rules.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] A type error occurs when an operation receives a different type of data than it expected.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] For example, a type error would happen if a line of code divides two integers, and is passed a string of letters instead of an integer.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] It is an unintended condition which might manifest in multiple stages of a program's development.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Thus a facility for detection of the error is needed in the type system.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] In some languages, such as Haskell, for which type inference is automated, lint might be available to its compiler to aid in the detection of error.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Type safety contributes to program correctness, but might only guarantee correctness at the cost of making the type checking itself an undecidable problem (as in the halting problem).
[src:yup-validation/type-system] In a *type system* with automated type checking, a program may prove to run incorrectly yet produce no compiler errors.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Division by zero is an unsafe and incorrect operation, but a type checker which only runs at compile time does not scan for division by zero in most languages; that division would surface as a runtime error.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] To prove the absence of these defects, other kinds of formal methods, collectively known as program analyses, are in common use.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Alternatively, a sufficiently expressive type system, such as in dependently typed languages, can prevent these kinds of errors (for example, expressing *the type of non-zero numbers*).
[src:yup-validation/type-system] In addition, software testing is an empirical method for finding errors that such a type checker would not detect.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The process of verifying and enforcing the constraints of types, *type checking*, may occur at compile time (a static check) or at runtime (a dynamic check).
[src:yup-validation/type-system] If a language specification requires its typing rules strongly, more or less allowing only those automatic type conversions that do not lose information, one can refer to the process as *strongly typed*; if not, as *weakly typed*.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The terms are not usually used in a strict sense.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Static type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program based on analysis of a program's text (source code).
[src:yup-validation/type-system] If a program passes a static type checker, then the program is guaranteed to satisfy some set of type safety properties for all possible inputs.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Static type checking can be considered a limited form of program verification (see type safety), and in a type-safe language, can also be considered an optimization.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] If a compiler can prove that a program is well-typed, then it does not need to emit dynamic safety checks, allowing the resulting compiled binary to run faster and to be smaller.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Static type checking for Turing-complete languages is inherently conservative.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Even if the expression `<complex test>` always evaluates to `true` at runtime, most type checkers will reject the program as ill-typed, because it is difficult (if not impossible) for a static analyzer to determine that the `else` branch will not be taken.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Consequently, a static type checker will quickly detect type errors in rarely used code paths.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Without static type checking, even code coverage tests with 100% coverage may be unable to find such type errors.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The tests may fail to detect such type errors, because the combination of all places where values are created and all places where a certain value is used must be taken into account.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] A number of useful and common programming language features cannot be checked statically, such as downcasting.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Thus, many languages will have both static and dynamic type checking; the static type checker verifies what it can, and dynamic checks verify the rest.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Many languages with static type checking provide a way to bypass the type checker.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Some languages allow programmers to choose between static and dynamic type safety.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] For example, historically C# declares variables statically, but C# 4.0 introduces the `dynamic` keyword, which is used to declare variables to be checked dynamically at runtime.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Other languages allow writing code that is not type-safe; for example, in C, programmers can freely cast a value between any two types that have the same size, effectively subverting the type concept.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Dynamic type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program at runtime.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Implementations of dynamically type-checked languages generally associate each runtime object with a *type tag* (i.e., a reference to a type) containing its type information.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] This runtime type information (RTTI) can also be used to implement dynamic dispatch, late binding, downcasting, reflective programming (reflection), and similar features.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Most type-safe languages include some form of dynamic type checking, even if they also have a static type checker.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The reason for this is that many useful features or properties are difficult or impossible to verify statically.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] For example, suppose that a program defines two types, A and B, where B is a subtype of A.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] If the program tries to convert a value of type A to type B, which is known as downcasting, then the operation is legal only if the value being converted is actually a value of type B.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Thus, a dynamic check is needed to verify that the operation is safe.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] This requirement is one of the criticisms of downcasting.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] By definition, dynamic type checking may cause a program to fail at runtime.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] In some programming languages, it is possible to anticipate and recover from these failures.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] In others, type-checking errors are considered fatal.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Programming languages that include dynamic type checking but not static type checking are often called "dynamically typed programming languages".
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Certain languages allow both static and dynamic typing.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] For example, Java and some other ostensibly statically typed languages support downcasting types to their subtypes, querying an object to discover its dynamic type and other type operations that depend on runtime type information.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] More generally, most programming languages include mechanisms for dispatching over different 'kinds' of data, such as disjoint unions, runtime polymorphism, and variant types.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Even when not interacting with type annotations or type checking, such mechanisms are materially similar to dynamic typing implementations.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Objects in object-oriented languages are usually accessed by a reference whose static target type (or manifest type) is equal to either the object's runtime type (its latent type) or a supertype thereof.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] This is conformant with the Liskov substitution principle, which states that all operations performed on an instance of a given type can also be performed on an instance of a subtype.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] This concept is also known as subsumption or subtype polymorphism.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] In some languages subtypes may also possess covariant or contravariant return types and argument types respectively.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Certain languages, for example Clojure, Common Lisp, or Cython are dynamically type checked by default, but allow programs to opt into static type checking by providing optional annotations.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] One reason to use such hints would be to optimize the performance of critical sections of a program.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The programming environment *DrRacket*, a pedagogic environment based on Lisp, and a precursor of the language Racket is also soft-typed.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Conversely, as of version 4.0, the C# language provides a way to indicate that a variable should not be statically type checked.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] A variable whose type is `dynamic` will not be subject to static type checking.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Instead, the program relies on runtime type information to determine how the variable may be used.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] In Rust, the `dyn std::any::Any` trait object provides dynamic typing of types containing no or only `'static` lifetimes.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The choice between static and dynamic typing requires certain trade-offs.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Static typing can find type errors reliably at compile time, which increases the reliability of the delivered program.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] However, programmers disagree over how commonly type errors occur, resulting in further disagreements over the proportion of those bugs that are coded that would be caught by appropriately representing the designed types in code.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Static typing advocates believe programs are more reliable when they have been well type-checked, whereas dynamic-typing advocates point to distributed code that has proven reliable and to small bug databases.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The value of static typing increases as the strength of the type system is increased.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Advocates of dependent typing, implemented in languages such as Dependent ML and Epigram, have suggested that almost all bugs can be considered type errors, if the types used in a program are properly declared by the programmer or correctly inferred by the compiler.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Static typing usually results in compiled code that executes faster.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] When the compiler knows the exact data types that are in use (which is necessary for static verification, either through declaration or inference) it can produce optimized machine code.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Some dynamically typed languages such as Common Lisp allow optional type declarations for optimization for this reason.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] By contrast, dynamic typing may allow compilers to run faster and interpreters to dynamically load new code, because changes to source code in dynamically typed languages may result in less checking to perform and less code to revisit.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] This too may reduce the edit-compile-test-debug cycle.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Statically typed languages that lack type inference (such as C and Java prior to version 10) require that programmers declare the types that a method or function must use.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] This can serve as added program documentation, that is active and dynamic, instead of static.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] This allows a compiler to prevent it from drifting out of synchrony, and from being ignored by programmers.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] However, a language can be statically typed without requiring type declarations (examples include Haskell, Scala, OCaml, F#, Swift, and to a lesser extent C# and C++), so explicit type declaration is not required for static typing in all languages.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Dynamic typing allows constructs that some (simple) static type checking would reject as illegal.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] For example, *eval* functions, which execute arbitrary data as code, become possible.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] An *eval* function is possible with static typing, but requires advanced uses of algebraic data types.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Further, dynamic typing better accommodates transitional code and prototyping, such as allowing a placeholder data structure (mock object) to be transparently used in place of a full data structure (usually for the purposes of experimentation and testing).
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Dynamic typing typically allows duck typing (which enables easier code reuse).
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Many languages with static typing also feature duck typing or other mechanisms like generic programming that also enable easier code reuse.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Dynamic typing typically makes metaprogramming easier to use.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] For example, C++ templates are typically more cumbersome to write than the equivalent Ruby or Python code since C++ has stronger rules regarding type definitions (for both functions and variables).
[src:yup-validation/type-system] This forces a developer to write more boilerplate code for a template than a Python developer would need to.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] More advanced runtime constructs such as metaclasses and introspection are often harder to use in statically typed languages.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] In some languages, such features may also be used e.g. to generate new types and behaviors on the fly, based on runtime data.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Such advanced constructs are often provided by dynamic programming languages; many of these are dynamically typed, although *dynamic typing* need not be related to *dynamic programming languages*.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Languages are often colloquially referred to as *strongly typed* or *weakly typed*.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] In fact, there is no universally accepted definition of what these terms mean.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] In general, there are more precise terms to represent the differences between type systems that lead people to call them "strong" or "weak".
[src:yup-validation/type-system] A third way of categorizing the type system of a programming language is by the safety of typed operations and conversions.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Computer scientists use the term *type-safe language* to describe languages that do not allow operations or conversions that violate the rules of the type system.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Computer scientists use the term *memory-safe language* (or just *safe language*) to describe languages that do not allow programs to access memory that has not been assigned for their use.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] For example, a memory-safe language will check array bounds, or else statically guarantee (i.e., at compile time before execution) that array accesses out of the array boundaries will cause compile-time and perhaps runtime errors.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] In this example, the variable `z` will have the value 42.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Although this may not be what the programmer anticipated, it is a well-defined result.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] If `y` were a different string, one that could not be converted to a number (e.g., "Hello, World"), the result would be well-defined also.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] A program can be type-safe or memory-safe and still crash on an invalid operation.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] This is for languages where the type system is not sufficiently advanced to precisely specify the validity of operations on all possible operands.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] But if a program encounters an operation that is not type-safe, terminating the program is often the only option.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] In this example `z` will point to a memory address five characters beyond `y`, equivalent to three characters after the terminating zero character of the string pointed to by `y`.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] This is memory that the program is not expected to access.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] In C terms this is simply undefined behaviour and the program may do anything; with a simple compiler it might actually print whatever byte is stored after the string "37".
[src:yup-validation/type-system] As this example shows, C is not memory-safe.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] As arbitrary data was assumed to be a character, it is also not a type-safe language.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] In general, type-safety and memory-safety go hand in hand.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] For example, a language that supports pointer arithmetic and number-to-pointer conversions (like C) is neither memory-safe nor type-safe, because it allows arbitrary memory to be accessed as if it were valid memory of any type.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Some languages allow different levels of checking to apply to different regions of code.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Additional tools such as lint and IBM Rational Purify can also be used to achieve a higher level of strictness.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] It has been proposed, chiefly by Gilad Bracha, that the choice of type system be made independent of choice of language; that a type system should be a module that can be *plugged* into a language as needed.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] He believes this is advantageous, because what he calls mandatory type systems make languages less expressive and code more fragile.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The requirement that the type system does not affect the semantics of the language is difficult to fulfill.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Optional typing is related to, but distinct from, gradual typing.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] While both typing disciplines can be used to perform static analysis of code (static typing), optional type systems do not enforce type safety at runtime (dynamic typing).
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The term *polymorphism* refers to the ability of code (especially, functions or classes) to act on values of multiple types, or to the ability of different instances of the same data structure to contain elements of different types.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Type systems that allow polymorphism generally do so to improve the potential for code re-use: in a language with polymorphism, programmers need only implement a data structure such as a list or an associative array once, rather than once for each type of element with which they plan to use it.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] For this reason computer scientists sometimes call the use of certain forms of polymorphism *generic programming*.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The type-theoretic foundations of polymorphism are closely related to those of abstraction, modularity and (in some cases) subtyping.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Many type systems have been created that are specialized for use in certain environments with certain types of data, or for out-of-band static program analysis.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Frequently, these are based on ideas from formal type theory and are only available as part of prototype research systems.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The following table gives an overview over type theoretic concepts that are used in specialized type systems.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The names M, N, O range over terms and the names $\sigma ,\tau$ range over types.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Also referred to as *dependent sum type*, since ${\textstyle (x:\sigma )\times \tau =\sum _{x:\sigma }\tau }$ .
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Dependent types are based on the idea of using scalars or values to more precisely describe the type of some other value.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] For example, $\mathrm {matrix} (3,3)$ might be the type of a $3\times 3$ matrix.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] where k, m, n are arbitrary positive integer values.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] A variant of ML called Dependent ML has been created based on this type system, but because type checking for conventional dependent types is undecidable, not all programs using them can be type-checked without some kind of limits.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Dependent ML limits the sort of equality it can decide to Presburger arithmetic.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Other languages such as Epigram make the value of all expressions in the language decidable so that type checking can be decidable.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] However, in general proof of decidability is undecidable, so many programs require hand-written annotations that may be very non-trivial.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] As this impedes the development process, many language implementations provide an easy way out in the form of an option to disable this condition.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] This, however, comes at the cost of making the type-checker run in an infinite loop when fed programs that do not type-check, causing the compilation to fail.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Linear types, based on the theory of linear logic, and closely related to uniqueness types, are types assigned to values having the property that they have one and only one reference to them at all times.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] These are valuable for describing large immutable values such as files, strings, and so on, because any operation that simultaneously destroys a linear object and creates a similar object (such as `str = str + "a"`) can be optimized "under the hood" into an in-place mutation.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Normally this is not possible, as such mutations could cause side effects on parts of the program holding other references to the object, violating referential transparency.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] They are also used in the prototype operating system Singularity for interprocess communication, statically ensuring that processes cannot share objects in shared memory to prevent race conditions.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The Clean language (a Haskell-like language) uses this type system to gain a lot of speed (compared to performing a deep copy) while remaining safe.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Intersection types are types describing values that belong to *both* of two other given types with overlapping value sets.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] For example, in most implementations of C the signed char has range -128 to 127 and the unsigned char has range 0 to 255, so the intersection type of these two types would have range 0 to 127.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Such an intersection type could be safely passed into functions expecting *either* signed or unsigned chars, because it is compatible with both types.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Such a function could be passed into another function expecting an "`int` → `int`" function safely; it simply would not use the "`float` → `float`" functionality.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] In a subclassing hierarchy, the intersection of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the most derived type.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The intersection of sibling types is empty.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The Forsythe language includes a general implementation of intersection types.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Union types are types describing values that belong to *either* of two types.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] For example, in C, the signed char has a -128 to 127 range, and the unsigned char has a 0 to 255 range, so the union of these two types would have an overall "virtual" range of -128 to 255 that may be used partially depending on which union member is accessed.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Any function handling this union type would have to deal with integers in this complete range.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] More generally, the only valid operations on a union type are operations that are valid on *both* types being unioned.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] C's "union" concept is similar to union types, but is not typesafe, as it permits operations that are valid on *either* type, rather than *both*.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Union types are important in program analysis, where they are used to represent symbolic values whose exact nature (e.g., value or type) is not known.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] In a subclassing hierarchy, the union of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the ancestor type.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The union of sibling types is a subtype of their common ancestor (that is, all operations permitted on their common ancestor are permitted on the union type, but they may also have other valid operations in common).
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Existential types are frequently used in connection with record types to represent modules and abstract data types, due to their ability to separate implementation from interface.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] For example, the type "T = ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }" describes a module interface that has a data member named *a* of type *X* and a function named *f* that takes a parameter of the *same* type *X* and returns an integer.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] These types are both subtypes of the more general existential type T and correspond to concrete implementation types, so any value of one of these types is a value of type T.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Given a value "t" of type "T", we know that "t.f(t.a)" is well-typed, regardless of what the abstract type *X* is.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] This gives flexibility for choosing types suited to a particular implementation, while clients that use only values of the interface type—the existential type—are isolated from these choices.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] In general it's impossible for the typechecker to infer which existential type a given module belongs to.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] In the above example intT { a: int; f: (int → int); } could also have the type ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Although abstract data types and modules had been implemented in programming languages for quite some time, it wasn't until 1988 that John C.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Mitchell and Gordon Plotkin established the formal theory under the slogan: "Abstract [data] types have existential type".
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The theory is a second-order typed lambda calculus similar to System F, but with existential instead of universal quantification.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] In a type system with Gradual typing, variables may be assigned a type either at compile-time (which is static typing), or at runtime (which is dynamic typing).
[src:yup-validation/type-system] This allows software developers to choose either type paradigm as appropriate, from within a single language.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Gradual typing uses a special type named *dynamic* to represent statically unknown types; gradual typing replaces the notion of type equality with a new relation called *consistency* that relates the dynamic type to every other type.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The consistency relation is symmetric but not transitive.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Many static type systems, such as those of C and Java, require *type declarations*: the programmer must explicitly associate each variable with a specific type.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Others, such as Haskell's, perform *type inference*: the compiler draws conclusions about the types of variables based on how programmers use those variables.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] For example, given a function `f(x, y)` that adds `x` and `y` together, the compiler can infer that `x` and `y` must be numbers—since addition is only defined for numbers.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Thus, any call to `f` elsewhere in the program that specifies a non-numeric type (such as a string or list) as an argument would signal an error.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Numerical and string constants and expressions in code can and often do imply type in a particular context.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] For example, an expression `3.14` might imply a type of floating-point, while `[1, 2, 3]` might imply a list of integers—typically an array.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Type inference is in general possible, if it is computable in the type system in question.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Moreover, even if inference is not computable in general for a given type system, inference is often possible for a large subset of real-world programs.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Haskell's type system, a version of Hindley–Milner, is a restriction of System Fω to so-called rank-1 polymorphic types, in which type inference is computable.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Most Haskell compilers allow arbitrary-rank polymorphism as an extension, but this makes type inference not computable.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] A type system that assigns types to terms in type environments using typing rules is naturally associated with the decision problems of type checking, typability, and type inhabitation.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Some languages like C# or Scala have a unified type system.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] This means that all C# types including primitive types inherit from a single root object.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Every type in C# inherits from the Object class.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Some languages, like Java and Raku, have a root type but also have primitive types that are not objects.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Java provides wrapper object types that exist together with the primitive types so developers can use either the wrapper object types or the simpler non-object primitive types.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Raku automatically converts primitive types to objects when their methods are accessed.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] A type checker for a statically typed language must verify that the type of any expression is consistent with the type expected by the context in which that expression appears.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] For example, in an assignment statement of the form `x := *e*`, the inferred type of the expression *`e`* must be consistent with the declared or inferred type of the variable `x`.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] This notion of consistency, called *compatibility*, is specific to each programming language.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] If the type of *`e`* and the type of `x` are the same, and assignment is allowed for that type, then this is a valid expression.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Thus, in the simplest type systems, the question of whether two types are compatible reduces to that of whether they are *equal* (or *equivalent*).
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Different languages, however, have different criteria for when two type expressions are understood to denote the same type.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] In languages with subtyping, the compatibility relation is more complex: If `B` is a subtype of `A`, then a value of type `B` can be used in a context where one of type `A` is expected (covariant), even if the reverse is not true.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] Like equivalence, the subtype relation is defined differently for each programming language, with many variations possible.
[src:yup-validation/type-system] The presence of parametric or ad hoc polymorphism in a language may also have implications for type compatibility.
